content.description: Flow up the face without using either edge. Some steep face moves.
content.protection: thin passive, small cams, or top rope anchor
content.location: South of Impossible crack is a gully and a slabby face.

content.description: Great crimpy climbing that keeps pushing you left and right.  The climb is 5.10b if you avoid the good holds to the right.  A well-set top-rope will get you this climb and INSIDE CORNER on one rope
content.location: The middle of the face left of inside corner

climbs.name: Softer Than Ice, Harder Than Diamonds

content.description: Short, but all of it is tough
content.protection: so thin, recommend top rope anchor
content.location: Work up the very left edge of Deuchler's corner North face

content.description: Start on the column just to the left of Lloyd's Lament. Sides of column are off. Ascend column up to saddle. Then heel hook and get on the saddle. A After standing on block, stand up left. Get 2 horizontal hand holds and reach far right hold then reach up for good hold. Further on a calf hold with a left gets good diag edge. Then scramble to the top. Always look left, nothing right.
There are two cruxes, one lower and one near the top
content.location: Starting from a small talus block, go up the center of this north facing wall to the top of the red streaks, then diagonal left

content.description:
Good beginner slab zig zags up the Inside Corner face on line of easiest holds. Diagonals left under the roof all the way to the left outside corner.  Follow easy corner holds to the top.   

  Variations Outside-In starts 5.8 on Rurp City face or corner and up then transition right to roof to finish on Inside Corner or Split the Difference.
content.protection: TR for true Outside Corner with Long Webbing.  Outside-In can be a trad lead 5.8.
content.location: Between Rurp City and Inside Corner zags left across Split the Difference. 25ft south of Batman on face with Inside corner.

content.description: A fairly sustained route that is harder towards the bottom.  A few long moves lead to solid holds.  Being tall is an advantage.
content.protection: For a TR you can sling any of the stable trees up top or some medium cams for the cracks.  A trad lead would be sketchy with the limited protection on the route.
content.location: Located on the arete past inside corner.

content.description: A great 5.4 to play on while waiting for some harder TR's around Deuchler's Corner area or a great route to take a beginner up. A direct start warrants a 5.6 but it is possible to head up at Cathuselum and then walk right on the slope-y ramp. The bulk of the climbing consists of a series of ledges. Most are very positive but a few are pretty slope-y and this is where a few good jams come in handy. It's almost dead vertical at that point so it makes for a fun climb. Finish by escaping right on easier terrain up top.
content.protection: Would take a few smaller cams about mid-route.
content.location: approx. 15ft to the right of  Cathuselum.

content.description: On the inside corner 30 feet or so down from Batman.

An easy climb, but a fun one for kids. Just a little difficult at the end, but otherwise just fun. To get to this route, you will find an access gully at the north end of the cliff. This is a 5.4 descent with a slightly tricky slab at the bottom, so you may want to hang some webbing for safety or even rope up. The first inside corner on the cliff with a big column at its base is where this climb starts.
content.protection: Excellent pro with slings nuts and hexes. Great beginners trad lead.Â

content.description: The crux is definitely the transfer into and out of the offwidth crack.  Some may find it useful to use a headjam and it is definitely a route you'll need some energy for.
content.protection: A few medium cams for the bottom. A #5 and an optional #6 C4 for the offwidth section.
content.location: Head to the Wisconsin strip and use the usual scramble decent, head past inside corner about 20 ft.  If you look up to your left you'll see an offwidth crack slightly overhanging and this is the route.

content.description: Once on the corner climb more or less straight up the right side of the corner, breaking right a little to succumb the roof - then back left up top.
content.protection: Toprope off trees and TCU's or Stoppers (longer webbing is nice for this corner).
content.location: Located on the corner to the left of Batman.   Start near the top of the approach slab (around the corner) and then bust up and right.

content.description: Reachy route, plan moves ahead
content.protection: so thin that i can only recommend top roping, but do what you will
content.location: Going straight up the thin crack on the north face(left of arete)

content.description: Climb straight up the corner, finishing on the left side of the arete.
content.protection: Toprope off trees and small TCU's or Stoppers (longer webbing is nice for this corner).
content.location: Start is the same place as Deuchler's Corner Right - on the left side of the corner to the left of Batman.  Don't break out right on the corner.

content.description: Climb the crack splitting the face on the lft side of the chimney.
content.location: You can't miss this prominent feature on the South end of the WI strip.

content.description: Good spot to bring beginners on the wisconsin side
content.location: On the far right side of the Wisconsin Strip

content.description: Head up the face to the the obvious jam crack at the top of the cliff.  This is the crux.  There's a way to avoid hand jams using the under cling.
content.location: Around the arete from inside corner look for the seam in the middle of the wall and the jam crack up high.

content.description: subtle slabby climbing that leads up to a powerful roof pull.  Obviously left of Cathuselum

A crimpy climb that starts out with an easy lay back on a crack and then hits the crux half way. The rest of the climb is then cruxy. A challenging climb. It is located just to the left of Lloyd's Lament and you use the corner of the column at the base of Lloyd's Lament for the start.

This prominent cliff on the Wisconsin shore of the St. Croix River is the furtherest north area on the Wisconsin side of Interstate State park.  This area contains a high concentration of long (by midwest standards) good quality routes, both leads and top rope problems.  This cliff is often quite busy with both climbers and hikers.
